XC332073-Goldfinch song and juv calls 15 July 2016 0640.mp3
rmk: An adult Goldfinch singing (almost invisibly) from within the canopy of a 3m tall Sycamore tree. An unknown number of others were within earshot, some of which were juveniles. Nesting had occurred nearby and the birds were probably from the same family group.  Richness in Goldfinch song is based upon fairly similar phrases that are either shortened or lengthened or have the ending 'tweaked'. At times I hear a resemblance to the terminal flourish that often characteristic of Chaffinch song. This bird was uttering random 'tickle-it' flight calls, woven into the song's delivery - peppering song with an occasional flight call is typical of Goldfinch. Examples can be heard at 0:04, 0:07 and 0:19 Goldfinches make a scolding 'hissy rattle' in situations of aggression, such as defending a feeder port.  A fleeting example of the sound can be heard at 0:40. From 0:50 to the end, the lilting tittering of juveniles can be heard. Other calls from, I assume, the same birds are at XC332135.
